The Eastern Desert is the arid region east of Midgaard, once irrigated by the Iseth Reach river whose drying destabilized the entire administrative system. The desert was governed by the Keepers of Measure before any dynastic empire — they used road stones calibrated to star angles, cistern basins, and water-right levies rather than coin. The Twelve Obelisk Lines served as legal instruments: shadows marked travel windows, ration allotment days, and convoy departure periods. The Salt Ledger Kingdoms succeeded the Keepers, building pyramid courts that fused trade administration with funerary ideology. The Ninth Meridian Doctrine — an attempt to anchor drought cycles through eclipse ritual — failed catastrophically, intensifying aridity and shattering road charter authority. The failed regent line militarized funerary priesthoods into the first Jackal Synod cadres. Modern layers: Synod toll courts controlling shrine-cistern nodes, Dune Reaver strongholds in old caravan forts, the Last Sand Regent as bound remnant intelligence still issuing decrees to a dead bureaucracy. Five ecological zones from west to east: charter road band with buried waystones, cistern archive ruins, convoy fortification remains, obelisk survey zone, and the Buried Court where the Regent waits. The Eastern Desert connects east to the Saltglass Reach and Mafdet, north to the pyramid complexes, and west to Midgaard via Roc Road. The desert is the historical core from which the wider desert civilization radiated.

