Midgaard archives preserve late-era expedition charters and salvage law tablets from the Eastern Desert. The city's pragmatic trade culture treated the collapsed desert road network as a resource extraction opportunity: survey crews were sent to map cistern ruins for recoverable stonework, and academic expeditions cataloged obelisk inscriptions. The Granite Arcade administrative offices hold Midgaard archival catalog numbers for salt ledger tablets removed from the desert, and some markers bear references to "shoreward certification" connecting the Eastern Desert's charter-stone network to the Saltglass Reach's three cairn lines. Midgaard road wardens' use of ritual boundary-sigil repainting — maintaining visible jurisdiction claims even when manpower prevents full repairs — derives from the same Stone Law principle that governed Eastern Desert obelisk maintenance: a road with marked instruments signifies recognized jurisdiction; an unmarked road signifies contested sovereignty. The "authorized thirst" toll vocabulary used in the Eastern Desert mirrors Midgaard's emergency rationing protocols, reflecting shared descent from Keeper-of-Measure administrative tradition. Eastern Desert conditions are reported to Midgaard through road warden intelligence channels, primarily relevant for their effect on Roc Road eastern-approach traffic patterns and caravan timing through the desert margin.

