Kowloon's Jade Magistracy maintains records of desert trade route law descending from the same Keeper-of-Measure legal tradition. The Neon Covenant's insistence on "one ledger, one ration code" echoes the Salt Ledger Kingdoms' water-debt accounting system; founding House Jien (the Jade Clerks) employed scribal methods directly imported from the desert's collapsed ledger courts. House Vao (the Grain Wardens) preserved diluted versions of the Eastern Desert's water arbitration law, adapted for grain and staple management. The Courier Lantern Office's registry methodology descends from the same census tradition that produced the desert's road-charter population counts. Kowloon caravan intelligence on Eastern Desert conditions is gathered via Midgaard relay; the city has no independent desert presence. The Ninth Meridian catastrophe's timeline is preserved in Kowloon records primarily as a commercial disruption event rather than a cosmological one: routes went silent, shipments stopped arriving, and it took years before the scope of the collapse was understood in northern cities. Kowloon's emergency rationing law explicitly cites the desert collapse as the historical case that justified codifying water-shortage protocols — the Eastern Desert is the cautionary precedent Kowloon's founders used to justify the Neon Covenant's distributive guarantees.

