Kiess Trade Syndics maintain commercial intelligence about eastern desert route conditions relayed through Midgaard's markets. The Temple of Concord preserves religious texts including fragments of Keeper-of-Measure survey prayers repurposed as civic benedictions — a survival pathway typical of how Keeper administrative vocabulary was absorbed into successor institutional liturgy. Kiess's primary interest in the Eastern Desert is the far end of the east-west trade logic: the desert routes connect through the Saltglass Reach to Mafdet's harbor, and cargo originating from or transiting through the desert reaches Kiess only after multiple intermediate validations. The Jackal Synod's "authorized thirst" toll courts represent a direct threat to that chain's continuity; Synod disruption of caravan traffic is tracked as a supply-route risk. Kiess has no direct charter claims east of the oasis corridor, and the desert's legal complexity — Keeper-era obelisk law, Ledger Kingdom water-right precedent, Synod toll courts, and Regent remnant decrees all operating simultaneously — places it outside Kiess's practical jurisdiction.

