Khenari death-rite geography in the Eastern Desert centers on the pyramid complexes and obelisk alignments as sacred directional infrastructure. The obelisk shadows marked not merely travel windows but transitions — the shadow's edge at specific solar positions was understood by pre-dynastic desert peoples as marking the moment when the living day shifted toward the territory of the dead. Khenari in Mafdet who trace origin to the eastern desert communities maintain seasonal observances tied to obelisk-shadow timing even without access to the physical obelisks. The Jackal Tribunal's system of three sentence classes — Interment (memory retained), Service (memory compressed), Correction (memory rewritten) — maps onto Khenari death-rite categories in ways that suggest shared descent from the same pre-dynastic funerary tradition. The failed Ninth Meridian Rite is preserved in Khenari oral tradition as the event that separated the living solar law from the dead underworld law: what had been one administrative system split into two irreconcilable theological factions, and the desert that had sustained both became the scar of their incompatibility.
